# Error Handling Rules

## Next.js Redirect Exception Rule
> [!WARNING]
> Next.js implements `redirect()` by throwing an error under the hood (`NEXT_REDIRECT`). If you use `try...catch` blocks in Server Actions and call `redirect()` inside the `try` block, the catch block will intercept it and break the intended navigation.

- **Mandatory Catch Block Handling**: Every `catch` block inside a Server Action must include the following check at the very top to re-throw Next.js redirect exceptions:
  ```typescript
  catch (error) {
    if (error && typeof error === "object" && "digest" in error && typeof error.digest === "string" && error.digest.startsWith("NEXT_REDIRECT")) { 
      throw error; 
    }
    // Handle other errors below
    console.error("Error context:", error);
    redirect(`/path?error=${encodeURIComponent("Friendly message.")}`);
  }
  ```

## Database Error Handling
- **Database Wrapper**: When making solitary Prisma calls that might fail unexpectedly, wrap them using `withDbErrorHandling` from `lib/db-error.ts` to provide generic fail-safes.
- **Explicit Logging**: Always log full error objects using `console.error("Context...", error)` before returning a generic error string to the user. Do not expose raw database error strings to the UI.

## Client-Side Error Presentation
- **URL Query Parameters**: The UI should consume `?error=` search parameters to display `Alert` or `Toast` components to the user. Do not rely heavily on React Error Boundaries for expected validation failures.
